      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain quantum entanglement to me? like im a student studying for a midterm. i dont need the math part just like what is it and how is it different from regular correlation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fundamental, concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine flipping two special, interconnected coins; when you check one and it lands on heads, you instantly know the other is tails, even if it's across the galaxy. The difference from regular correlation is that in the quantum case, the properties of the particles aren't decided until the moment you measure one of them. This instantaneous connection is what Einstein famously called \"spooky action at a distance.\"",
